										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<h3>What is the Python Range function?</h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Python range() is an inbuilt function that generates a sequence of numbers. When we call the range function in Python, it creates an <a href="https://searchapparchitecture.techtarget.com/definition/object-oriented-programming-OOP" target="_blank" rel="noopener external" data-wpel-link="external">object</a> of a range of numbers and it </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">takes</span> <span style="font-weight: 400;">the arguments of start, stop and the step i.e </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">range(start, stop, step).</span></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><iframe loading="lazy" title="Python range – Python tutorial for beginners – CodeBerry Programming School" width="1080" height="608" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/CP4LKSVaeZA?feature=oembed" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen></iframe></p>
<h3>How to create Python Range?</h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">We can create a list of numbers using the range function, however, it is important to note that the stop number will not be included in the list.</span></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><iframe loading="lazy" src="https://trinket.io/embed/python/b2008d53e0?start=result" width="100%" height="300" frameborder="0" marginwidth="0" marginheight="0" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen"><span data-mce-type="bookmark" style="display: inline-block; width: 0px; overflow: hidden; line-height: 0;" class="mce_SELRES_start">﻿</span></iframe></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">If we change the start number to two then we will obtain a list of even numbers as shown in the code below.</span></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><iframe loading="lazy" src="https://trinket.io/embed/python/915221e08e?start=result" width="100%" height="300" frameborder="0" marginwidth="0" marginheight="0" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen"><span data-mce-type="bookmark" style="display: inline-block; width: 0px; overflow: hidden; line-height: 0;" class="mce_SELRES_start">﻿</span></iframe></p>
<h3><span style="font-weight: 400;">Using a for loop to create a range of numbers</span></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">This is particularly useful when we want to add things together or maybe we want</span> <span style="font-weight: 400;">to add a number to a string for various reasons.</span> <span style="font-weight: 400;">The best way that we can do that is by using a for loop.</span></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><a href="https://codeberryschool.com/en/python-programming-course-for-beginners" target="_blank" rel="noopener external" data-wpel-link="external"><img loading="lazy" class="aligncenter wp-image-11995 size-full" src="https://codeberryschool.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Python-1.png" alt="Python" width="1024" height="340" srcset="/blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Python-1.png 1024w, /blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Python-1-300x100.png 300w, /blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Python-1-768x255.png 768w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></a></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">So we&#8217;re going to do </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">for x in range()</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">.</span> <span style="font-weight: 400;">Now what this is going to do, is every loop through x is going to become the next number in our</span> <span style="font-weight: 400;">range because we&#8217;re using a list. Let’s do a range of 1,10.</span> <span style="font-weight: 400;">This is going to go look through each of the numbers, one through nine just as in the example above.</span></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><iframe loading="lazy" src="https://trinket.io/embed/python/2ffb5a9877?start=result" width="100%" height="300" frameborder="0" marginwidth="0" marginheight="0" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen"><span data-mce-type="bookmark" style="display: inline-block; width: 0px; overflow: hidden; line-height: 0;" class="mce_SELRES_start">﻿</span></iframe></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">We can also add numbers using a loop and the Python range function. We can simply do that by changing the print statement to read print(x+5).</span></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><iframe loading="lazy" src="https://trinket.io/embed/python/33c076134d?start=result" width="100%" height="300" frameborder="0" marginwidth="0" marginheight="0" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen"><span data-mce-type="bookmark" style="display: inline-block; width: 0px; overflow: hidden; line-height: 0;" class="mce_SELRES_start">﻿</span></iframe></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">We can also create a descending list by simply changing the step within the range function to be a negative number. For instance, if we change the step to -1 it is going to count from ten up to but not including 1.</span></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><a href="https://codeberryschool.com/en/python-programming-course-for-beginners" target="_blank" rel="noopener external" data-wpel-link="external"><img loading="lazy" class="aligncenter wp-image-12197 size-full" src="https://codeberryschool.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Python-2.png" alt="" width="1024" height="340" srcset="/blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Python-2.png 1024w, /blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Python-2-300x100.png 300w, /blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Python-2-768x255.png 768w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></a></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><iframe loading="lazy" src="https://trinket.io/embed/python/eb3e283d57?start=result" width="100%" height="300" frameborder="0" marginwidth="0" marginheight="0" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen"><span data-mce-type="bookmark" style="display: inline-block; width: 0px; overflow: hidden; line-height: 0;" class="mce_SELRES_start">﻿</span></iframe></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">So if we wanted to go all the way down we needed to change the stop number to Zero.</span></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><iframe loading="lazy" src="https://trinket.io/embed/python/081dda5694?start=result" width="100%" height="300" frameborder="0" marginwidth="0" marginheight="0" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen"><span data-mce-type="bookmark" style="display: inline-block; width: 0px; overflow: hidden; line-height: 0;" class="mce_SELRES_start">﻿</span></iframe></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">We can also append this number to a text which can be quite useful depending on what you&#8217;re doing.</span> <span style="font-weight: 400;">To do that we need to print the word item and then use an additional sign to concatenate it with the integer being printed out by first converting it to a string, as illustrated in the code below. When we execute this code we’ll end up with</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"> a list of items with a number on the end.</span></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><iframe loading="lazy" src="https://trinket.io/embed/python/160d46974e?start=result" width="100%" height="400" frameborder="0" marginwidth="0" marginheight="0" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen"><span data-mce-type="bookmark" style="display: inline-block; width: 0px; overflow: hidden; line-height: 0;" class="mce_SELRES_start">﻿</span></iframe></p>
